Jazz is not derived from orchestral and march music with blues and ragtime influences, it #8217;s the other way around.

The people who played early jazz were not in orchestras or formal brass bands, this assimilation happened later when musicians started leading jazz orchestras. The brass bands that played early jazz never previously played European music in a classical music sense, and it certainly wasn #8217;t orchestras that started playing jazz. The brass bands that you #8217;re referring to were generally already street musicians getting together and improvising. I also hate to make this distinction, but it #8217;s very important: jazz didn #8217;t start with white musicians in classical settings incorporating African-American musical concepts like improvisation and the blues, but when an African-American base of rhythm and blues used certain European harmonic concepts.

Wynton Kelly's or Miles Davis' solos on Freddie Freeloader are fantastic beginner solos. While his solos get very difficult technically, learning the first few choruses of a Keith Jarrett solo on a blues is great for learning how to create melodies over the changes. For chords, you can't beat accompaniment by Wynton Kelly (the Miles album Someday My Prince Will Come is a fantastic example), Bill Evans, Red Garland, or Tommy Flanagan. For more 60s post-bop oriented language and harmony, check out McCoy Tyner and Herbie Hancock. Lastly, if you want to check out the greatest pianists and keyboardists working today, take a look at Aaron Parks, Robert Glasper, Brad Mehldau, or Christian Sands. There are so many more than what I mentioned, but hopefully this can give you a good starting point.
